:"CEM097","plot_notes":"Jay Family Cemetery, Rye NY — interred spring 2022"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD1641","mother_id":"I00176"},"marriages":[],"tags":["educator","environmentalist"],"sources":[{"label":"Jay Heritage Center — Remembering Jane-Kerin Moffat","url":"https://jayheritagecenter.org/2022/01/09/remembering-jane-kerin-moffat-1931-2021/"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["social_reform","education"],"notable_blurb":"Saved John Jay's estate from demolition","primary_url":"https://jayheritagecenter.org/2022/01/09/remembering-jane-kerin-moffat-1931-2021/","primary_url_label":"Jay Heritage Center"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"She saved her ancestor John Jay's childhood home","body":"Jane-Kerin Moffat was a direct descendant of John Jay, first Chief Justice of the United States. In the 1980s, the 23-acre Jay Estate in Rye, New York — where Jay had spent his childhood — was slated for development. She spent thirteen years rallying 65 environmental, historic, and government groups into the Jay Coalition.","number":1},{"header":"She coordinated 180 organizations to protect Long Island","body":"As coordinator of the National Audubon Society's Long Island Sound Watershed Alliance, Jane-Kerin Moffat organized over 180 groups and held hearings along the Connecticut and New York coastline to document the degradation of the Sound. She co-authored the resulting report and convened a Citizens Summit that drew 200 environmentalists and legislators from both states. The National Audubon Society gave her its Audubon Activist Award and published a feature article about her in 2000.","number":2}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Doctor Jane-Kerin Moffat","first_name":"Jane-Kerin","last_name":"Moffat","maiden_name":"Moffat","married_names":[],"title":"Doctor"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],